==Other works==

A made-for-television movie, ''[[Farewell to Manzanar]]'', aired on March 11, 1976, on [[NBC]]. It was based on the 1973 memoir of the same name, written by [[Jeanne Wakatsuki Houston]], who was imprisoned at Manzanar as a child, and her husband James D. Houston.<ref name = "FarewellMovie">{{cite web | title = Farewell to Manzanar (1976) (TV) | publisher = National Broadcasting Corporation | url = http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0074518 | accessdate = January 12, 2008}}</ref> The book and the movie tell the story of the Wakatsuki family and their experiences behind the barbed wire through young Jeanne's eyes.<ref name = "FarewellBook">{{cite book | author = Houston, Jeanne Wakatsuki | title = Farewell To Manzanar: A True Story of Japanese American Experience During and After the World War II Internment | publisher = Laurel Leaf | year = 1973, 1983 | isbn = 0-553-27258-6}}</ref><ref name = "DiscoverNikkeiJWH">{{cite web | title = Discover Nikkei: Jeanne Wakatsuki Houston | url = http://www.discovernikkei.org/en/interviews/profiles/61/ | publisher = DiscoverNikkei.org | date = November 25, 2006 | accessdate = November 18, 2010}}</ref>

''[[Come See The Paradise]]'' was a feature film about how forced relocation and imprisonment at Manzanar affected a Japanese American family from Los Angeles and a European American union organizer. The film, released in 1990, starred [[Dennis Quaid]] and [[Tamlyn Tomita]], and was written and directed by Alan Parker.<ref name = "Paradise">{{cite web | title = Come See The Paradise (1990) | publisher = Twentieth-Century Fox Film Corporation | url = http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0099291 | accessdate = September 24, 2007}}</ref>

The 1994 award-winning novel, ''[[Snow Falling on Cedars]]'' by David Guterson, contains many scenes and details relating to Japanese Americans from the [[Puget Sound]], [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]], area and their internment experiences at Manzanar.<ref name = "Cedars">{{cite book | author = Guterson, David | title = Snow Falling On Cedars | publisher = Vintage | year = 1995 | isbn = 0-679-76402-X}}</ref>  The [[Snow Falling on Cedars (film)|2000 film]] based on the book also details that connection.<ref name = "Snow">{{cite web | title = Snow Falling On Cedars (1999) | publisher = The Kennedy-Marshall Company/Universal Studios | url = http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0120834 | accessdate = September 24, 2007}}</ref>

[[Fort Minor]]'s song "[[Kenji (song)|Kenji]]", from the album ''[[The Rising Tied]]'' (2005), tells the true story of [[Mike Shinoda]]'s family and their experiences before, during, and after World War II, including their imprisonment at Manzanar.<ref name=" ShinodaInterview">{{cite news | title = MorleyViews: Interviews by Morley Seaver: Mike Shinoda (Linkin Park, Fort Minor) | publisher = AntiMusic/Iconoclast Entertainment Group | url = http://www.antimusic.com/morley/05/FortMinor.shtml | accessdate = September 24, 2007}}</ref>

The Asian American jazz fusion band [[Hiroshima (band)|Hiroshima]] has a song entitled "Manzanar" on its album ''The Bridge'' (2003). It is an instrumental song inspired by Manzanar and the Japanese American internment.<ref name = "HiroshimaBridge">{{cite web | title = Bridge | publisher = Hiroshima, Inc. | url = http://www.hiroshimamusic.com/bridgereview.html | month = October | year = 2003 | accessdate = May 27, 2007}}</ref>  Also, its song "Living In America", on its album titled ''East'' (1990), contains the phrase "I still remember Manzanar."

[[Channel 3 (band)|Channel 3]]'s song titled "Manzanar" is about the internment.<ref name = "Channel3">{{cite web | title = Song Meanings <U+2013> Lyrics <U+2013> Channel 3 <U+2013> Manzanar | publisher = SongMeanings | url = http://www.songmeanings.net/lyric.php?lid=3530822107858628118 | date = September 30, 2006 | accessdate = September 24, 2007}}</ref>

A 2007 episode of the [[CBS]] television crime drama ''[[Cold Case (TV series)|Cold Case]]'', titled "Family 8108", dealt with the 1945 murder of a Japanese American man in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] after he and his family were released from Manzanar. The episode originally aired on December 9, 2007.<ref name = "ColdCasetv.com">{{cite web | title = Cold Case: Family 8108 - TV.com | url = http://www.tv.com/cold-case/family-8108/episode/1142751/summary.html | year = 2007 | accessdate = December 10, 2007}}</ref>

Folk/country musician [[Tom Russell]] wrote "Manzanar", a song about the Japanese American internment, that was released on his album ''Box of Visions'' (1993).<ref name = "Billboard.com">{{cite web | title = Box of Visions <U+2013> Tom Russell (1993) | url = http://www.billboard.com/song/tom-russell/manzanar/11908130#/album/tom-russell/box-of-visions/144904 | publisher = Billboard | date = April 10, 2003 | accessdate = May 2, 2010}}</ref>  [[Laurie Lewis]] covered the song on her album ''Seeing Things'' (1998), adding the Japanese string instrument, the [[koto (musical instrument)|koto]], to her performance.<ref name = "BlueGrassWorks">{{cite web | author = Geffen, Lewis| title = Laurie Lewis | url = http://www.bluegrassworks.com/profile.php?profileID=26 | publisher = Bluegrass Works LLC | date = January 1, 2004 | accessdate = December 24, 2007}}</ref>

